description.text:
Took jneilliii's 40mm fan remix of the Lion4H original and shortened the fangs by 8mm as Lion4H describes to make it compatible with the FLSun i3. Make sure to check out their designs (which should be linked on the left there) for instructions on how to modify it to your needs using Blender and the attached file, and don't forget to thank them while you're at it! It works great, best thing short of dual-blower (see below). Enjoy!

It is designed to be used with the stock e3d v5 clone hotend, or v6 upgrade (using BFAL's lowering holder), 40mm heatsink fan, and 5015 blower fan that come with the FLSun i3*.

*I HIGHLY recommend you replace the original 5015 that comes with the kit with a better 12V, ~.15A unit, I did not realize how bad it was until I got a pair that push some real CFM.

Short - Nozzles located slightly high, shooting air down sides of nozzle and forming a slightly turbulent downward column about 1" wide

Mid-Length - A happy medium on my machine; bubble around the nozzle forming a downward column about 1" wide

Long - Not as much air right around the sides of the nozzle but focused right below it, forming a downward column about 1" wide.

You can also find my v5 compatible low-profile heatsink fan shroud here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2243045

v6 HSF shroud here:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2721378

For extreme, tuneable cooling, check out my Radian Fan Tornado; a dual-blower parts cooler with interchangeable, customizable ducts, and twice the cooling potential of the RFF: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2725848

I've seen it printed laying flat as well, I assume with supports under the 40mm fan mount.

description.text:
This is a customizable version of Make Anything's Satisfying Twist Container in OpenSCAD. The shape, height, radius, smoothness and twist can be customized. Demo video.

The generated models are solid (filled in) and need to be printed in Vase Mode. In Cura this is called 'Spiralize Outer Contour' (but currently has some bugs).

You need customize the line width (nozzle size), deviation (gap between parts) and bottom layer height to fit your printer and print settings. The default deviation (gap between parts) is set to 0.3 mm but can be changed. 0.3 mm gives fairly tight fit on larger prints on my printer (Ultimaker 2 clone). Notice that the tightness also depends on the part size. Larger parts have more surface area.

The model includes a base and chamfers on the inner part. The chamfer angles are quite high (63°) and should print nicely. The chamfer depth and height can also be customized if you need to.

Open in customizer to customize dimensions and generate STL files.

Idea totally stolen from Make Anything.

title: Prusa i3 Y-Carriage motor mount / aligner / base bearing

description.text:
The original Y-motor part from my oldie Prusa-I3 broke while I was doing some maintenance work (DOH!). I knew the motor pulley was a bit missaligned with the Y-belt due to the original part design lack of support to keep straight the motor (if you know what I mean...). As I was already cleaning and adjusting the machine's base and have broken the original part I designed a new one with a support part to keep the motor in place. No supports required. Fits as the original part but a bit sturdier. Just print the motor and support part and tighten them with the m8 nuts, and exactly the same M3 screws as the original setup, (no need for longer screws). This time I know the motor won't become misaligned any more, no bitting of belt's teeth or unwanted vibrations. Recommended print in ABS with at least 50% infill. FreeCAD sources included as usual. No changes expected for this, I just printed and installed, it worked nicely. There are out there some removable fixing parts that doesn't require disassembly of the back of the machines base, they simply are push fit. I didn't like that solution because push fit parts could pop out from machines working 24/7. As I wanted a permanent & secure solution I simply designed a support engaged in the M8 rods, this way it won't pop out from that critical part ot the machine stopping the Y carriage freedom. Pics shows different color parts as I was in a hurry and printed each part in any of my other machines as they became available. Sorry about all the mess on my workbench, but it's just that, a workbench...

Enjoy!

description.text:
After being dissatisfied with the cludgy belt attachment on the G2S, which requires punching holes in the belt, I saw the lovely self-locking-belt design in http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1582570 but wanted something that mounted solidly to the existing components and didn't rely on new parts or friction-fit anywhere.

The resultant set of belt clamps mount to the aluminium block on the sliders using the original screws, and don't need any other modifications.

There are three versions - generally I'd suggest the "slimline" version, as my original non-slimline model causes a 2mm lateral belt offset which -might- introduce scaling errors at the top of prints; I've not done the maths to confirm, but better safe than sorry, personally.
The "slimline extended" version I'd suggest if you're already dealing with pre-cut belts, as otherwise I think the belt length in the original kit might be too short.

title: Fein FMM Dust Exhaust to Festool ShopVac 36mm Adapter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is an adapter to connect a Fein Multimaster's dust exhaust to a Festool CTL 26 shop vac.

The Fein Multimaster (350 QSL) is indeed shipped with a dust exhaust, which is good, but without any adapters to connect to shop vac hoses with differing diameters. This is bad.

BTW: If you buy the dust exhaust set separately you will get two adapters to connect the exhaust to differently sized hoses. An interesting and annoying marketing detail.

So I rolled my own adapter to connect the FMM's dust exhaust to a Festool hose connector with 36mm diameter. Actually, Festool declares the hose diameter to be 36/32mm but remeasuring revealed an inner diameter of 39mm. So the adapter you find here goes from a cone-shaped 28/24mm to 39mm.

description.text:
During printing larger or heavier items i noticed some wobble on the x/y axis. This was in fact coming from the z runners.

Soooo a quick fix was to insert a couple of sliders to reduce this movement.
Foam type sticky pads are required. Some space was allowed for this. Some doubling up of pads may be required to give a snug fit. Dont make it to tight though as this may create other issues.

!!! When installed check the left block does not hit the z top switch !!!

description.text:
I created this PVC funnel to solve a real-world problem: Normal funnels aren't long enough! I needed a way to pour boiling water into our home's clothes washer drain to clear out detergent buildup (someone's been using too much!). Because the drain is in a tight spot it's all but impossible to pour a pot of boiling water (slowly) into it. Normal funnels are either too wide to fit into the cavity above the drain or their spouts are too skinny/short (e.g. "ain't nobody got time for that!").

Using a length of 1/2-inch PVC pipe solves this problem entirely but taping a funnel to the pipe never works for long (at least, not with boiling water!). Hence, the custom-made PVC funnel.

It should fit nice and tightly around 1/2" PVC pipe and has an internal taper to ensure nothing leaks; no need to cement it! I tested it with SCH-40 PVC but SDR-21 (thin wall) should work too.

Note: I uploaded a transparent render of the model so it would be easier to see the internal taper and how that works.

title: MKS Gen L v1.0 Board Case

description.text:
I designed this case to hold the MKS Gen L V1.0 board on the Flsun I3. The measurements for the board's mounting holes are 103mm x 75mm. The front cover has mounting holes for a 92mm fan. I'm using the Arctic F9 92mm. Mount it facing outward so it's pulling air out instead of pushing air in. I left the fan on the outside with a grill on the cover so as not to accidentally have wires hitting the fan blades. This way, you won't be adding more cooling to whatever you're printing.

There are several different versions depending on how you'd want to route the wires. There's also a separate fan cover as well.

Updated with V2. One with hotend wires mount up top and another one with just multiple holes in case you need to have the wires coming out of different sides.

Update again for V2. Added 10mm extra depth to hold all the wires in without bulging. Also added a cover for the 92mm fan.

Update - Case Cover V2 was missing a hole. :)

I'd recommend PETG as the board does get pretty warm.

Today I would like to show you a printable Rocker Blotter. I suppose people who love the "calligraphy world" will know what it is, and how useful it may become. For people who don't know about it, a rocker blotter is an antique tool, used to dry the ink which doesn't dry so fast. With this tool, you avoid to damage your work letting rests of ink all around the paper. I made the code in C++, using the new OOML library (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:17761 http://iearobotics.com/oomlwiki). So, If you want to change some of the parameters (measures) or work with this code to made some derivated or new desings, you should download this libray. Afterwards, you only have to open de project and modify the independent parameters (in RockerBlotter.cpp). However, I also add too the OpenScad generated code; although I think it isn't very intuitive to change. (I really advise you to work with OOML).

Here you have the .stl in separated files:
  • the RockerBlotter
  • an elegant holder -> ATTENTION: Work in progress*. Still doesn't parametric at all.
  • the RockerBlotter with a basic and funcional holder (cause you can print it together).
    • Or if you want, you can print it directly from the stl. The standard size is:
  • wide: 30 mm
  • Diameter: 80 mm
  • Thickness: 2.5 mm
    • I've printed one with these dimensions and it works perfectly!!! =) If you print the elegant holder, you must remove carefully the external plastic. I added it just for made this printable. Just add the blotter paper, and join the two pieces. If there is still some free space, you can fold the blotter paper. Here you can see how to do it: http://youtu.be/oWe8voROtQM Print it and improve the results of your calligraphy works!

description.text:
This is designed to be printed in copperfil or bronzefil (Colorfab). Bring into your slicer then size according to the coin size you want....it starts out as 1 cm so if you wanted 3 cm diameter scale to 3x. Scale large enough to get the detail you want out of your printer resolution head size and layer height. A good setting for me on the Lulzbot Mini is 3x, .2 mm layer height, 200C print temp, 60C bed temp, 25mm/sec print speed no support or adhesion.

After the coins print, there are two methods to glue...use Seal All glue or if you are good with a blowtorch lay the side with the subliminal RB on it on tile face down and hit it with a 2 second blast of flame then take the other half and set on top face up. Press together gentle and allow to set. After either glue method, take a soildering iron and go around the edges to seal up and eliminate the seam. Finally toss the coin in a glass of bleach (chlorine) and leave a day or two....speed it up by pulling it out and letting it dry a few times during that period.

When the coin has the patina of being in the sea for centuries, then you can preserve it with a coat of non-glossy polyurethane paint/sealer or just leave it as is. Enjoy and spread the word about Reef Balls to help save and create marine habitat.

title: Prusa MK2 I3 Heatbed Cover Groing

description.text:
After I have repeatedly broken the Prusa heating bed covers, and finally the cables from the heating bed torn, I decided to redesign the cover.
In my design, I have made sure that the screw does not break so quickly from the cover. In addition, I have taken care that the 3mm filament is attached further back and the recording can not break out so quickly.
On the cover, there are great forces during the printing process, which it must take up the cover.
In the case of the original part, this ultimately failed to total cable breakage, which led to a change of the heating bed with subsequent rewiring.
Greeting JFW Blaschke

Nachdem mir immer wieder die Heizbettabdeckungen von Prusa zerbrochen sind, und letztendlich dabei die Kabel vom Heizbett abgerissen sind, habe ich mich entschieden die Abdeckung neu zu gestalten.
Bei meinem Design habe ich darauf geachtet das die Schraube nicht mehr so schnell aus dem Cover bricht. Außerdem habe ich darauf geachtet das das 3mm Filament weiter hinten angebracht ist und die Aufnahme nicht mehr so schnell ausbrechen kann.
Auf dem Cover wirken nämlich während des Druckvorganges große Kräfte, die das Cover aufnehmen muss.
Bei dem Originalteil hat das nämlich letztendlich zum totalen Kabelabriss geführt, was einen Wechsel des Heizbettes mit anschließender Neuverkabelung geführt hat.
Gruß JFW Blaschke

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.4 nozzle

Infill:

100%

Notes:

This is a completely new design, which I have completely redesigned.
There is only so much to say about the parameters of 3D printing. In these dimensions it is advisable to print with 100% infill.
Support is actually not necessary.
The connections on the MK42-Heatbed also give no more space. Of the dimensions, the cover is slightly wider and the cable recording has become somewhat more stable. On the other hand, I have not changed anything in height because the print head should not collide with the cover when the print surface is used.

Dies ist ein völlig neues Design welches ich komplett neu konstruiert habe. Zu den Parametern des 3D Drucks ist nur so viel zu sagen, In diesen Dimensionen ist es Ratsam mit 100 % Infill zu drucken.
Support ist eigentlich nicht nötig.
Die Anschlüsse auf dem MK42-Heatbed geben ja auch nicht mehr Platz her. Von den Dimensionen ist das Cover ein wenig breiter und die Kabelaufnahme etwas stabiler geworden. In der Bauhöhe habe ich dagegen nichts verändert, da der Druckkopf nicht bei Ausnutzung der Druckfläche mit der Abdeckung kollidieren soll.

Material:

It is better to print the cover in ABS because ABS tolerates more heat than PLA. Do not cover the cover after installation with zip-ties to the cables. This ensures that the cables are unloaded and can no longer be torn off.

V9 is now the final version of my cover.

Es ist besser das Cover in ABS zu drucken, da ABS mehr Hitze verträgt als PLA.Vergesst nicht das Cover nach dem Einbau mit Kabelbindern an den Kabeln zu sichern. Dies stellt sicher dass die Kabel entlastet werden und nicht mehr abreissen können.

V9 ist jetzt die Finale Version meines Covers.

title: Replicator 2X active cooling fan duct - front discharge

description.text:
This is an active cooling fan solution for the Replicator 2X. It is similar to the design by ten13th except it is made to work with any 40mm front-discharge fan. It is secured in place with two of the long hex bolts from the extruder, and the fan is secured to the duct using the bottom 2 screws.  
I tried initially to use the MakerBot motherboard's cooling fan relay, however this is a 24V output so it should only be used with 40mm cooling fans rated for 24V. The relay did not seem to respond well when I connected a 12V voltage regulator to it in an attempt to use a 12V 40mm fan (which is much more common). To avoid damage to the mobo, I have the cooling fan now connected to an external power source.  
The front-discharge fans are not as efficient as side-discharge fans due to the drastic reduction in flow cross-sectional area. This design will provide a gentle flow for moderate cooling (e.g. for making small ABS or large PLA parts); however, if you need more air flow (e.g. for small or detailed PLA prints), a side-discharge fan is recommended.

Print Parameters:
  • Lay the model in MakerWare face down with inlet port flat on print surface and exhaust ports pointing up
  • ABS 0.2mm layer thickness with infill density 0.3
  • Rafts and supports are recommended
  • Support angle set to 60 degrees with density of 0.2
  • To avoid print lifting, set raft outset to 6mm
    • Additional parts:
  • Digikey part #259-1566-ND 40mm 12VDC fan
  • Any 12VDC household power supply
  • Switch (optional)
    • Assembly instructions:
  • Remove raft and support carefully
  • Remove the inner 2 hex bolts from the extruder head (picture)
  • Clean the fan duct bolt holes and thread the hex bolts through
  • Tighten the hex bolts and secure duct to the extruder head (pictures)
  • Split the wire ends of the 12VDC and solder (or twist together) with ends of the fan
  • Mount the fan on the duct using the 2 bottom screw holes (pictures)
    • Optional - if using MakerBot fan cooling relay:
  • Any 24V 40mm fan e.g. DigiKey #381-2367-ND
  • Turn the Rep 2X on its side, preferably its right side when looking at the machine from the front
  • Take off the 4 bolts at the bottom holding the protective cover of the motherboard (see picture)
  • Locate the cooling fan relay connector and connect your fan to it.
  • Warning: the cooling fan relay does not handle much load (which can be concern especially when printing dual extrusion), there have been frequent reports of this relay failing (FET burning out). When this happens the circuit will fail closed. As such, when the fan is turned "OFF" there will still be about 17-18V across the leads; the fan will still turn, but it will rotate at a lower RPM. When the fan is turned "ON" there will be about 24V across the leads. In other words, the cooling fan will never shut off if the FET relay fails. It's probably safer if you implement an external power source separate from the Rep 2X.

title: 90mm printed quadcopter frame for br1103 motors

description.text:
I got bit by the nano/piko/femto quad bug and had to make one. I liked the look of @microdure's frame, but it was bigger than I wanted. I had already started working up a very minimal frame design and printed it as 80/90/100 mm....but didn't notice the motor shaft on the BR1103 motors extended through the base. Since I had to redraw my motor mounts anyway I decided to try and design a frame more like microdure's only in the 80-100mm range since a bit of motor protection would be nice to have knowing how often I crash things.

Frame is an easy print, that takes just under an hour on my printer at 0.25mm layer height. I also included some small m3 spacers that make it possible to use the TX-02 camera mount I included as a source.

You will need to have o-rings under your FC for clearance - or you could mount it upside down or remove the DSM port. I used O-rings. The FC mounting holes are slightly undersized from M3 since I used an M3 tap to thread them then mounted the FC with nylon screws. You could drill them out and use nuts on the bottom if you don't have a tap.

With a 450mah 2s battery, LemonRX DSM sat RX, and TX-02 FPV cam/VTX this comes in right at 80g ready to fly when printed in PLA with 15% infill

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25

Infill:

15%

Notes:

So far this has held up better than I anticipated printed in PLA with 3 perimeters and 15% infill. I've crashed it full throttle into my house and sidewalk several times and the frame hasn't broken yet. I may try printing it in ABS since it should be lighter and a bit tougher...but PLA has worked great so far in a few days of crash testing.

As noted in the description you'll probably want to use an M3 tap to thread the mounting posts.

I also drilled out the motor mounting holes - they're sized properly in the STL but 1st layer squish tends to block them up a bit. A #52 or #53 drill bit works great. The motor shafts cleared the center holes fine but I cleaned them up with a #57 drill just to be safe.

I used a LemonRX DSM satellite RX which I removed the connector from so it would fit easier inside the frame under the FC.

This was designed in Onshape and the design is available here:

https://cad.onshape.com/documents/0ff58260891f62cc5d956c69/w/6c0088ba3a61f0eb9aca2b9d/e/6b1820b07c502b2d5d3d3fe6

I used the STL of microdure's frame to transfer the motor mount dimensions, ID of the motor shrouds, and FC footprint.

The design can easily be adjusted for different motor to motor sizes. My first build was 100mm motor to motor and flew well, but I wanted to shrink it a bit smaller so I resized it to 90mm which is as small as I could go and still fit 2030 props comfortably.
